\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \vec{X}$
\end_inset

 is displacement in space time from point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 We Shall define components with respect to observer 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \vec{X} \mathop = \limits^{\boldsymbol{\cdot}}_{O} \left(t_Q-t_P,X_Q-X_P,Y_Q-Y_P,Z_Q-Z_p\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above equation can be written in compact notation i.e
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \vec{X} \mathop \rightarrow \limits^{}_{O} \Delta {X^{\mu}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu \in \left[ t,x,y,z\right]$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu \in \left[ 0,1,2,3\right]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Usually 0 corresponds to time whereas 1,2,3 may denote other orthogonal coordinate system.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Different Inertial Observer:
\series default

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \vec{X}$
\end_inset

 are geometric objects exists independent of representation.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \vec{X} \mathop \rightarrow \limits^{}_{\overline{O}} \Delta {X^{\overline{\mu}}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{O}$
\end_inset

 components are related by lorentz transformation as given below:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta {X^{\overline{0}}}=\gamma {\Delta X^0} - \gamma\ v\ {\Delta X^1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta {X^{\overline{1}}}=-\gamma\ v\ {\Delta X^0} + \gamma{\Delta X^1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta {X^{\overline{2}}}={\Delta X^2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta {X^{\overline{3}}}={\Delta X^3}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The above set of transformation holds good for reference frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{O}$
\end_inset

 moving along axis 1 with speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 along axis 1 as seen by observer 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma  = \left[\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-v^2}}\right]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 here 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is light speed unit as defined earlier.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Better compact notation:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[\Delta X^{\overline{\mu}}=\sum_{\nu = 0}^{3}\Lambda^{\overline{\mu}}_{\nu}\ \Delta X^{\nu}\]
\end_inset

or writing in simple way of Einstein Summation convention: Repeated indices in upstairs and downstairs positions are summed from 0 to 3. 
\begin_inset Formula \[\Delta X^{\overline{\mu}}=\Lambda^{\overline{\mu}}_{\nu}\ \Delta X^{\nu}\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[\Lambda^{\overline{\mu}}_{\nu}=\frac{\delta X^{\overline{\mu}}}{ \delta X^{\nu}}\]
\end_inset

the above equation will be used in transformation from one reference frame to other.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is dummy index, however 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is not the dummy index sometimes called free index. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Spacetime Vector:
\series default
 Any quartet of numbers (i.e components) which transforms between Inertial reference Frame like displacement Vector.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{A} \mathop = \limits^{}_{O} \left(A^0,A^1,A^2,A^3\right)\mathop \rightarrow \limits^{}_{O} {A^{\alpha}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\overline{\mu}}=\Lambda^{\overline{\mu}}_{\alpha}.A^{\alpha}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 decides the component of Vector with respect to observer 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 then, it also requires linearity rules
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 i.e If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}$
\end_inset

 are two vectors then their sum
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{C}=\vec{A}+\vec{B}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 is also a vector.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Further if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{A}$
\end_inset

 is a vector and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a scaler then their product is a vector.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{D}=a.\vec{A}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Note:
\series default
 the scaler quantity should be same for all frame of reference/observers. This means mass cannot be taken as scaler.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
